{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17622594","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17622594"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:03:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:03:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16806"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16806","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16806"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.67,0.05,0.17,0.02,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9497"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101636"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9497","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9497"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16806"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84077"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4938"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5205"},{"type":"tags","id":"10293"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22430"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22810"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101636","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101636"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman is scheduled for elective cholecystectomy. The anaesthetist plans to use propofol for induction of general anaesthesia. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the drug\u0027s primary mechanism of action?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Potentiates inhibitory neurotransmitters GABA and glycine","Inhibits calcium channels in presynaptic terminals","Blocks sodium channels in neuronal membranes","Activates potassium channels causing hyperpolarisation","Antagonises glutamate receptors"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EUnlike most other anaesthetic agents, the mechanism of action of propofol is not well understood. It is known to achieve its clinical effects primarily through \u003Cstrong\u003Epotentiating the inhibitory transmitters GABA and glycine\u003C/strong\u003E. This increases GABA-mediated chloride ion flow into neurons, causing hyperpolarisation and decreased neuronal excitability, leading to rapid sedation and unconsciousness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibiting calcium channels in presynaptic terminals\u003C/strong\u003E: while propofol may have minor effects on calcium channels, this is not its primary mechanism of anaesthetic action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking sodium channels in neuronal membranes\u003C/strong\u003E: this represents the primary mechanism of local anaesthetic agents rather than propofol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivating potassium channels causing hyperpolarisation\u003C/strong\u003E: although this would cause neuronal inhibition, it is not a significant mechanism for propofol\u0027s anaesthetic effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntagonising glutamate receptors\u003C/strong\u003E: whilst propofol may have some modulatory effects on glutamate signalling, this is not its principal mechanism of action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPropofol\u0027s high lipid solubility allows it to rapidly cross the blood-brain barrier, leading to quick onset of action. Its effects are terminated primarily through redistribution to peripheral tissues, followed by hepatic metabolism.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Propofol acts primarily by enhancing GABA-mediated chloride currents, causing rapid sedation and unconsciousness.","Propofol has a rapid onset and short duration due to its high lipid solubility and redistribution.","Propofol causes dose-dependent cardiovascular depression through vasodilation and negative inotropy."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84077"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16806"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84077","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84077"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-03T15:27:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-03T15:28:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9497"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101636"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"